SIMPLE: ligature
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ligature
<hw>Lig"a*ture</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧g"⟦adot⟧*t⟦usl⟧r; 135)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>ligatura</ets>, fr. <ets>ligare</ets>,
<ets>ligatum</ets>, to bind: cf. F. <ets>ligature</ets>. Cf.
<er>Ally</er>, <er>League</er>, <er>Legatura</er>, <er>Liable</er>,
<er>Ligament</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of binding.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything that binds; a band or bandage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A thread or string
for tying the blood vessels, particularly the arteries, to prevent
hemorrhage.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A thread or wire used to remove
tumors, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The state of being bound or stiffened; stiffness;
<as>as, the <ex>ligature</ex> of a joint</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Impotence caused by magic or charms.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A curve or line connecting notes;
a slur.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>A double character, or a type
consisting of two or more letters or characters united, as
<it>⟦ae⟧</it>, <it>⟦filig⟧</it>, <it>⟦ffllig⟧</it>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ligature</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ligature
<hw>Lig"a*ture</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧g"⟦adot⟧*t⟦usl⟧r)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>To ligate; to tie.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lige</ent>⟦br⟧
